    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1971-05-03T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1971-05-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="225"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d225">
                <head>225. Memorandum From the Presidentʼs Assistant for National Security Affairs
                        (<persName corresp="#p_KHA1" type="from">Kissinger</persName>) to President
                        <persName corresp="#p_NRM1" type="to">Nixon</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d225fn1">Source: National Archives, <persName
                            corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, Box 733, Country Files—Europe,
                        Yugoslavia, Vol. II Aug 70–Aug 71. Confidential. Sent for action. <persName
                            corresp="#p_HBGAM1">Haig</persName> initialed the memorandum for
                            <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1971-05-03">May 3, 1971</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Financial Assistance for Yugoslavia</item>
                </list>
                <p>Secretary <persName corresp="#p_RWP1">Rogers</persName> (Tab A)<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d225fn2">Attached but not printed.</note> recommends your approval
                    of a $61 million debt rescheduling for Yugoslavia ($59 million of <gloss
                        target="#t_PL1">PL</gloss>–480 and $2 million of Development Loan Fund
                    principle and interest). The figure represents 44% of the $140 million
                    Yugoslavian debt to <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> government agencies
                    coming due in 1971 and 1972. Equal payments on the postponed amounts would be
                    stretched out over a 10-year period beginning in 1973. A 5% interest rate would
                    be charged during the repayment period.</p>
                <p>Yugoslavia is currently soliciting about $600 million in Western aid, of which
                    80% would come from Europe and 20% or $120 million from the <gloss
                        target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> over the next two years. Politically, our
                    assistance would signal to the Yugoslavs, Eastern Europeans and the Soviets the
                    importance we place on the success of Yugoslaviaʼs political and economic
                    decentralization efforts and her moves toward an essentially open market
                    economy. Economically, it would help Yugoslavia over a severe balance of
                    payments crisis by increasing reserves from the present dangerously low level.
                    This would, in turn, assist her economic stabilization program and thereby allow
                    her to continue the economic reforms on which she has embarked. The rescheduling
                    would be done in conjunction with an <gloss target="#t_IMF1">IMF</gloss> standby
                    agreement and in cooperation with other creditors.</p>
                <p>We have also offered Yugoslavia a Commodity Credit Corporation (<gloss
                        target="#t_CCC1">CCC</gloss>) credit line increase of $20 million, a new
                        <gloss target="#t_CCC1">CCC</gloss> barter program of $25 million, an
                    increase in <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> military procurement, and an
                    increase in <gloss target="#t_ExImBank1">Ex-Im Bank</gloss> lending. With these
                    programs, the total 1971 <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> government
                    financial contribution to Yugoslavia would increase by $110 million, although
                    only the $30 million debt rescheduling for the year represents the <hi
                        rend="italic">direct</hi> assistance for its reserve problem which the
                    Yugoslavs consider their most important requirement. We cannot do <pb
                        facs="0602" n="558" xml:id="pg_558"/> more simply because present
                    legislation flatly bars any <gloss target="#t_AID1">AID</gloss> money for
                    Yugoslavia, and there are no other available options.</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <hi rend="italic">Recommendation</hi>
                </p>
                <p>That you approve Secretary <persName corresp="#p_RWP1">Rogers</persName>ʼ
                    recommendation of a $61 million debt rescheduling for Yugoslavia. <persName
                        corresp="#p_PP1">Pete Peterson</persName> and Treasury concur. Agriculture
                    has no objection.<note n="3" xml:id="d225fn3">The President initialed the
                        approval option on May 4.</note>
                </p>
            </div>
